A: You can use a while loop instead of a for loop to achieve this. The Iterator.next() method will throw a NoSuchElementException when there are no more elements to iterate over, so you can catch this exception and reset the iterator when it is thrown.

Here is the corrected code:

```java
char res;
int ctr = 10;
char[] flames = {'F','L','A','M','E','S'};

Iterator<Character> iterator = Arrays.asList(flames).iterator();

while(ctr > 0){
    try {
        res = iterator.next();
        jLabel1.setText(String.valueOf(res));
        ctr--;
    } catch (NoSuchElementException e) {
        iterator = Arrays.asList(flames).iterator();
    }
}
```

This code will go back to the first index of the array when it reaches the end. The iterator is reset to the beginning of the array every time a NoSuchElementException is thrown, which happens when the end of the array is reached.

Note: This code assumes that the number of iterations you want is less than or equal to the length of the array. If you want to iterate more than the length of the array, you will need to add additional logic to handle that.

